[1] ENE-COVID19: Seroepidemiology study [Spain]
Date: Thu 2 Jul 2020
Source: La Moncloa [in Spanish, machine trans., edited]
https://www.lamoncloa.gob.es/serviciosdeprensa/notasprensa/sanidad14/Documents/2020/040620-ENE-COVID_Informe2.pdf


Summary
- ENE-Covid19 is a comprehensive longitudinal study of population-based sero-epidemiology, whose objectives are to estimate the prevalence of infection by SARS Cov2 by determining antibodies against the virus in Spain and evaluating its temporal evolution. The results presented today [Thu 2 Jul 2020], for the 2nd round, refer to the reading of the IgG band of the rapid test.
- In the ENE-Covid second round (18 May to 1 Jun 2020), 63 564 participants were recruited in the national sample and 3355 in the island-specific study, not included in this report. The participation rate among eligible individuals has been 66.5% (improving the 1st round 63.7%), and considering only the people who have been contacted reaches 76.1% (it also represents an improvement of 2 points compared to observed in the 1st round: 74.9%).
- The improvement in the participation rate reflects, on the one hand, a high adherence to the study (95% of the participants of the 1st round have accepted to participate in the 2nd) and the incorporation of 5847 participants who were not present in round 1. As many as 87.9% of the participants have agreed to provide a blood sample (55 854 samples in the national study and 3106 more in the island-specific study) .
- The estimated prevalence of IgG antibodies against SARS-Cov2 in Spain is 5.2% (95% CI: 4.9%-5.5%). Slightly lower for men 5% (95% CI: 4.6% -5.4%) than women for 5.4% (95% CI: 5.0% -5.8%). In relation to age, the prevalence is lower in babies, children and young people, with moderate differences in it among the rest of the older groups. In relation to the diagnosis or COVID19 by PCR, 80.5% of the participants who reported having had a PCR + more than 2 weeks ago presented IgG antibodies.
- In possible suspected cases, the prevalence increases with the number of symptoms and is particularly high in those who report anosmia (40%). 2.8% of the participants without any symptoms presented IgG antibodies, which implies that about one 33% of SARS-CoV-2 infections are asymptomatic.
- Although the national prevalence is 5.2%, there is a marked geographic variability similar to that observed in round 1. In the provincial maps the central grouping stands out again of provinces with prevalences equal to or close to 10% in the Madrid environment. In relation to participants from round 1, initially negative and who have converted, the overall percentage is 0.8% (95% CI: 0.7% -0.9%), highlighting a percentage close to 2% in √Åvila, Valladolid and Palencia, and 1.5% in Madrid, Soria and Gerona.
- In relation to the municipal size, we observed very similar prevalences to the 1st round in all cases, except for a slight increase in the large cities (more than 100,000 inhabitants) that have gone from a prevalence of 6.4% (95% CI: 5.8-7.1) to 6.8% (95% CI: 6.2-7.4).
- The map of possible cases with COVID19 symptoms in the last 2 weeks (people with 3 or more symptoms compatible with COVID19 or with sudden loss of smell) shows lower prevalences than those observed in the 1st round. Only the provinces of Santa Cruz de Tenerife, Granada, Madrid, Toledo and Las Palmas are around 1%.
- These results must be considered provisional since they do not have the information that will provide the determination of IgG anti SARS-CoV2 antibodies measured by immunoassay.
- This study is the result of the effort of many professionals and the trust and generosity of more than 60 000 participants who have understood the interest of providing time, information and samples to learn about the situation of the COVID19 epidemic in our country.
- The chosen rapid test (Orient GeneIgM / IgG, from the company ZhejiangOrient Gene Biotech) has, according to the manufacturer, a sensitivity of 88% and 97% to determine IgM and IgG respectively, and a specificity of 100%. In reliability studies carried out for ENE-Covid19, a sensitivity of 73% and 79% respectively for IgM or IgG, with a specificity of 98% for IgM and 100% for IgG, was reported.
- The study also includes an epidemiological survey with background information and symptoms related to Covid19. In the report we used as a definition of a possible case of COVID19 the concurrence of 3 or more symptoms described in COVID19 patients or the sudden presence of anosmia. A recent case of COVID19 is considered to be a person who reports the presence of these symptoms in the last 2 weeks.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[ENE-Covid19 is a large population-based sero-epidemiological longitudinal study, whose objectives are to estimate the prevalence of SARS-Cov2 infection by determining antibodies against the virus in Spain, in each of the Autonomous Communities and in each province. , providing information by age and sex, and assessing changes in prevalence over three separate waves over time.
This report includes preliminary results obtained in the second round of the study, which has taken place in the 2 weeks between 18 May [2020] and 1 Jun [2020]. To facilitate comparison with round 1, the results of that round are included in the tables.
There are detailed tables on the data analysis as well as Figures on the provincial map of IgG anti SARS-CoV2 Antibodies in round 2 and provincial map of participants with sero-conversion against SARS-CoV2 in round 2 (IgG-round 1 and IgG + round 2). As more and more planned sero-prevalence studies area conducted in the effected countries , much needed information on the immune response to COVID-19 in exposed populations will become available, thereby guiding control measures including vaccination strategies-Mod.UBA]

