Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In the past 24 hours, according to the report at the source URL, the tally of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in South Korea has increased by 44 cases with 1 new death, compared with 48 cases and 1 new death in the previous day (5 Jul 2020). The daily newly confirmed case count has been at or below 100 for 84 consecutive days. There were 20 locally transmitted cases: Gyeonggi (7), Gwangju (6), Seoul (3), Incheon (2), and Daejeon (2), and 24 imported cases -- airport quarantine (16), Gyeonggi (6), Jeollabuk (1), and Deagu (1). There were 10 provinces reporting no newly confirmed cases.

According to data from the "ncov" website of the Ministry of Health and Welfare, the cumulative confirmation rate has been steady at 1.0% http://ncov.mohw.go.kr/.

The overall impression hasn't changed: Lifting of measures has been accompanied by increases in locally acquired infections through increasing clusters related to gatherings of people at employment (bringing it outside employment to contacts) and in houses of worship, and bars and clubs. But, that being said, importations are also playing a major role in the country. It would be nice to know the asymptomatic rate being detected, and the proportion of asymptomatic infections detected that go on to clinical disease.

Tabular and graphic analyses of the situation in South Korea with the addition of the 63 newly confirmed cases from 5 Jul 2020 are available at the English language page (https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030), notices 419 and 420. There are analyses of the country-wide situation including the newly confirmed cases and listings of current ongoing clusters. A total of 3 of the clusters mentioned are related to religious gatherings, 1 related to an elementary school, 1 related to an office building, 1 related to a nursing home, 1 related to an apartment complex and 1 linked to a Sauna facility.

The (presumed) location of infection acquisition of the 24 new imported cases are: America (6), Europe (1), and Asia excluding China (17) (Kazakhstan=13; Philippines=3; Pakistan=1).

Takeaway message: Importations continue to be a challenge, and gatherings whether social or religious are key foci for enlarging clusters (unchanged from previous 3 day's message).

A map of South Korea showing provinces can be seen at https://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/korea-south-administrative-map.htm and a HealthMap/ProMED map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7549897,195. - Mod.UBA]

